	Translation (version 1 by Renato)
	
Prosperity! Fortune! 
In the tenth year of the king Rājarāja-kesari-panmaṉ, who apportioned pots in Kāntaḷūr-cālai. 
This is the handwriting of the villagers from Vēḷkaḷa-veṇpākkam, next to holy Govintapāṭi in Tāmar-nāṭu[…].The account regarding Piṭavūr-nāṭu, on the northern border of Cōḻa-nāṭu, [is the following:] 
This year, the received gift was this 20 marked (tuḷai) gold [coins] because of the endowment order for [this] quality gold under our responsability, fixed by (kaiyāl) Arunilai Śrīkṛṣṇaṉ, alias Muvēnta Piṭavūr, owner of […]. 
Three kaḻañcus of gold came each year through interest, being that the first [of them came] in the month of Puraṭṭāti, the second [through] monthly [interest], and one through annual interest. 
Let the trustees–in charge of the temple (śrīkāryam ceykiṉṟa) of the Lord [which will] every year as long as the sun and the moon last–be appointed as collectors (taṇṭi) of the interest of three kaḻañcus of gold so that one kaḻañcu is for the heads of the temple (kōyil nampimār), to which they dedicated (kēṭppitta) the holy hymn, and two kaḻañcus for the leaders of the assembly (paridai nāyakaṉmār), who performed (āṭiṉa)–on the seventh day of the holy festival–the holy hymn (tiruppatiyam) that begins with kōlanaṟkuḻal, composed(viṇṇapam ceyta) by the devotee (āḻvāṉ) of holy Govintapāṭi, Kāyāvāṉ Arunilai, alias Muvēnta Piṭavūr Vēḷār, donor (appaṉār) of this gold. 
If we appoint [them], let them be the chosen for receiving the tax[…], needed for You[…], the temple managers that, by royal order, keep them hidden. 
May we become the designated duty bearers (kaṭavōm) of this allowance (nivantam) that covers the tax (taṇṇtam) imposed by them. 
We, the villagers of Vēḷkaḷa-Veṇpākkam, gave to Muvēnta Piṭavūr Vēḷār [this endowment] after agreeing in this way. 
I am the master of Āṟaiyaṉ of holy Govintapāṭi, the one who has handwritten in the stone, as indicated by the villagers. It is my writing. 
This is for the protection of the holy vaiṣṇavas. 
